The paper deals with a distributed-memory matrix multiplication algorithm that is designed to handle irregular data structures, which is relevant for fast methods in quantum physics. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper's focus on task-based formulation and load balancing suggests that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper's use of the Scalable Universal Matrix Multiplication Algorithm (SUMMA) and its relevance to high-performance computing suggests that it could belong to the Scientific Computing (cs.SC) sub-category. The paper's use of multiple-issue scheduling and fine-grained task-based formulation suggests that it could also belong to the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the paper's relevance to machine learning and quantum physics suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
